# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: medical-imaging-modalities
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] A **contrast agent** (or **contrast medium**) is a substance used to increase the contrast of structures or fluids within the body in medical imaging.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] Contrast agents absorb or alter external electromagnetism or ultrasound, which is different from radiopharmaceuticals, which emit radiation themselves.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] In X-ray imaging, contrast agents enhance the radiodensity in a target tissue or structure.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] In magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), contrast agents shorten (or in some instances increase) the relaxation times of nuclei within body tissues in order to alter the contrast in the image.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] Contrast agents are commonly used to improve the visibility of blood vessels and the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] The types of contrast agent are classified according to their intended imaging modalities.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] For radiography, which is based on X-rays, iodine and barium are the most common types of contrast agent.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] Various sorts of iodinated contrast agents exist, with variations occurring between the osmolarity, viscosity and absolute iodine content.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] Non-ionic dimers are favored for their low osmolarity and low toxicity, but have a correspondingly higher cost attached to their use.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] Gadolinium is used in magnetic resonance imaging as an MRI contrast agent or gadolinium-based contrast agent (GBCA).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] In the 3+ oxidation state, the metal has seven unpaired electrons.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] This causes water around the contrast agent to relax quickly, enhancing the quality of the MRI scan.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] Microbubbles are used as contrast agents for sonographic examination, specifically echocardiograms, for the detection of a cardiac shunt.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] These microbubbles are composed of agitated saline solution, most of which are too large to pass through the capillaries (blood vessels) of the lungs.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] Therefore, the only ones that reach the left side of the heart pass through an abnormal connection between the two sides of the heart, known as a right-to-left shunt.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] In addition, pharmaceutically prepared microbubbles are composed of tiny amounts of nitrogen or perfluorocarbons strengthened and supported by a protein, lipid, or polymer shell.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] These are small enough to pass through the capillaries and are used to increase the contrast in the left ventricle, improving the visualization of its walls.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] The drop in density on the interface between the gas in the bubble and the surrounding liquid strongly scatters and reflects the ultrasound back to the probe.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/contrast-agent] This process of backscattering gives the liquid with these bubbles a high signal, which can be seen in the resulting image.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The DICOM standard has been widely adopted by hospitals, large clinics, and the medical software industry.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] It is sometimes used in smaller-scale applications, such as dentists' and doctors' offices.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DICOM is also used in veterinary medicine and in research.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA) holds the copyright to the published standard, which was developed by the DICOM Standards Committee (which includes some NEMA members).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] It is also known as NEMA standard PS3 and as ISO standard 12052:2017: *"Health informatics – Digital imaging and communication in medicine (DICOM) including workflow and data management"*.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DICOM is used worldwide to store, exchange, and transmit medical images.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DICOM has been central to the development of modern radiological imaging; DICOM incorporates standards for imaging modalities such as radiography, ultrasonography, computed tomography (CT), magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), and radiation therapy.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DICOM includes protocols for image exchange (e.g., via portable media such as DVDs), image compression, 3-D visualization, image presentation, and results reporting.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DICOM is a standard developed by the American College of Radiology (ACR) and the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] In the beginning of the 1980s, it was difficult for anyone other than manufacturers of computed tomography or magnetic resonance imaging devices to decode the images that the machines generated.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Radiologists and medical physicists sought the images for dose-planning in radiation therapy.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] ACR and NEMA collaborated and formed a standard committee in 1983.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Their first standard, ACR/NEMA 300, entitled "Digital Imaging and Communications", was released in 1985.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Very soon after its release, it became clear that improvements were needed.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The text was vague and had internal contradictions.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] In 1988 the second version was released.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] This version gained more acceptance among vendors.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The image transmission was specified as over a dedicated 2 pair cable (EIA-485).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The first demonstration of ACR/NEMA V2.0 interconnectivity technology was held at Georgetown University, May 21–23, 1990.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Six companies participated in this event, DeJarnette Research Systems, General Electric Medical Systems, Merge Technologies, Siemens Medical Systems, Vortech (acquired by Kodak that same year) and 3M.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Commercial equipment supporting ACR/NEMA 2.0 was presented at the annual meeting of the Radiological Society of North America (RSNA) in 1990 by these same vendors.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Many soon realized that the second version also needed improvement.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Several extensions to ACR/NEMA 2.0 were created, like Papyrus (developed by the University Hospital of Geneva, Switzerland) and SPI (Standard Product Interconnect), driven by Siemens Medical Systems and Philips Medical Systems.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The first large-scale deployment of ACR/NEMA technology was made in 1992 by the US Army and Air Force, as part of the MDIS (Medical Diagnostic Imaging Support) program based at Ft.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Loral Aerospace and Siemens Medical Systems led a consortium of companies in deploying the first US military PACS (Picture Archiving and Communications System) at all major Army and Air Force medical treatment facilities and teleradiology nodes at a large number of US military clinics.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DeJarnette Research Systems and Merge Technologies provided the modality gateway interfaces from third party imaging modalities to the Siemens SPI network.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The Veterans Administration and the Navy also purchased systems from this contract.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] In 1993 the third version of the standard was released.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Its name was then changed to "Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine", abbreviated DICOM.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] New service classes were defined, network support added and the Conformance Statement was introduced.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Initially the DICOM standard was referred to as "DICOM 3.0" to distinguish it from its predecessors.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DICOM has been constantly updated and extended since 1993, with the intent that changes are backward compatible, except in rare cases where the earlier specification was incorrect or ambiguous.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Officially there is no "version" of the standard except the current standard, hence the "3.0" version number is no longer used.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] There are no "minor" versions to the standard (e.g., no such thing as "DICOM 3.1") and there are no current plans to develop a new, incompatible, version of the standard (i.e., no "DICOM 4.0").
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The standard should be referenced without specification of the date of release of a particular published edition, except when specific conformance requirements are invoked that depend on a retired feature that is no longer documented in the current standard.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] While the DICOM standard has achieved a near universal level of acceptance among medical imaging equipment vendors and healthcare IT organizations, the standard has its limitations.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DICOM is a standard directed at addressing technical interoperability issues in medical imaging.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] It is not a framework or architecture for achieving a useful clinical workflow.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The Integrating the Healthcare Enterprise (IHE) initiative layered on top of DICOM (and HL-7) defines profiles to select features from these standards to implement transactions for specific medical imaging interoperability use cases.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Though always Internet compatible and based on transport over TCP, over time there has been an increasing need to support port 80 HTTP transport to make use easier within the web browser.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Most recently, a family of DICOM RESTful web services have been defined to allow mobile device friendly access to DICOM objects and services, which include WADO-RS, STOW-RS and QIDO-RS, which together constitute the DICOMweb initiative.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] There are some derivations from the DICOM standard into other application areas.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] These include DICONDE (*Digital Imaging and Communication in Nondestructive Evaluation*) that was established by ASTM International and DICOS (*Digital Imaging and Communication in Security*).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DICONDE was established in 2004 as a way for nondestructive testing manufacturers and users to share image data.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DICONDE can be used for computed radiography, digital radiography, computed tomography, ultrasonic testing, eddy-current testing, and thermographic testing.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DICONDE is used worldwide to store, send, and exchange data from nondestructive material testing.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Unlike DICOM in the medical field, the adoption of DICONDE has been slower due to the lack of regulatory requirements for manufacturer-independent interoperability.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DICONDE is also gaining importance in the context of Industry 4.0 due to its extensive capabilities for networking systems from different manufacturers.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DICOS was established in 2009 to be used for image sharing in airport security, cargo scanning, and other security applications.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The standard is published by the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA) as NEMA IIC 1, and was developed in cooperation with the U.S.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Department of Homeland Security's Science and Technology Directorate and the Transportation Security Administration (TSA).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DICOM groups information into data sets.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] For example, a file of a chest x-ray image may contain the patient ID within the file, so that the image can never be separated from this information by mistake.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] This is similar to the way that image formats such as JPEG can also have embedded tags to identify and otherwise describe the image.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] A DICOM data object consists of a number of attributes, including items such as name, ID, etc., and also one special attribute containing the image pixel data (i.e. logically, the main object has no "header" as such, being merely a list of attributes, including the pixel data).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] A single DICOM object can have only one attribute containing pixel data.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] For many modalities, this corresponds to a single image.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] However, the attribute may contain multiple "frames", allowing storage of cine loops or other multi-frame data.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Another example is NM data, where an NM image, by definition, is a multi-dimensional multi-frame image.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] In these cases, three- or four-dimensional data can be encapsulated in a single DICOM object.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Pixel data can be compressed using a variety of standards, including JPEG, lossless JPEG, JPEG 2000, and run-length encoding (RLE).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] LZW (zip) compression can be used for the whole data set (not just the pixel data), but this has rarely been implemented.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DICOM uses three different data element encoding schemes.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] With explicit value representation (VR) data elements, for VRs that are not OB, OW, OF, SQ, UT, or UN, the format for each data element is: GROUP (2 bytes) ELEMENT (2 bytes) VR (2 bytes) LengthInByte (2 bytes) Data (variable length).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] For the other explicit data elements or implicit data elements, see section 7.1 of Part 5 of the DICOM Standard.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The same basic format is used for all applications, including network and file usage, but when written to a file, usually a true "header" (containing copies of a few key attributes and details of the application that wrote it) is added.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] To promote identical grayscale image display on different monitors and consistent hard-copy images from various printers, the DICOM committee developed a lookup table to display digitally assigned pixel values.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] To use the **DICOM grayscale standard display function (GSDF)**, images must be viewed (or printed) on devices that have this lookup curve or on devices that have been calibrated to the GSDF curve.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] In addition to a value representation, each attribute also has a *value multiplicity* to indicate the number of data elements contained in the attribute.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] For character string value representations, if more than one data element is being encoded, the successive data elements are separated by the backslash character "\".
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DICOM consists of services, most of which involve transmission of data over a network.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The file format for offline media is a later addition to the standard.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The DICOM Store service is used to send images or other persistent objects (structured reports, etc.) to a picture archiving and communication system (PACS) or workstation.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The DICOM storage commitment service is used to confirm that an image has been permanently stored by a device (either on redundant disks or on backup media, e.g. burnt to a CD).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The Service Class User (SCU: similar to a client), a modality or workstation, etc., uses the confirmation from the Service Class Provider (SCP: similar to a server), an archive station for instance, to make sure that it is safe to delete the images locally.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] This enables a workstation to find lists of images or other such objects and then retrieve them from a picture archiving and communication system.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The DICOM modality worklist service provides a list of imaging procedures that have been scheduled for performance by an image acquisition device (sometimes referred to as a modality system).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The items in the worklist include relevant details about the subject of the procedure (patient ID, name, sex, and age), the type of procedure (equipment type, procedure description, procedure code) and the procedure order (referring physician, accession number, reason for exam).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] An image acquisition device, such as a CT scanner, queries a service provider, such as a RIS, to get this information which is then presented to the system operator and is used by the imaging device to populate details in the image metadata.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Prior to the use of the DICOM modality worklist service, the scanner operator was required to manually enter all the relevant details.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Manual entry is slower and introduces the risk of misspelled patient names, and other data entry errors.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] A complementary service to modality worklist, this enables the modality to send a report about a performed examination including data about the images acquired, beginning time, end time, and duration of a study, dose delivered, etc.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] It helps give the radiology department a more precise handle on resource (acquisition station) use.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Also known as MPPS, this service allows a modality to better coordinate with image storage servers by giving the server a list of objects to send before or while actually sending such objects.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The DICOM print service is used to send images to a DICOM printer, normally to print an "X-Ray" film.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] There is a standard calibration (defined in DICOM Part 14) to help ensure consistency between various display devices, including hard copy printout.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The format for offline media files is specified in Part 10 of the DICOM Standard.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Such files are sometimes referred to as "Part 10 files".
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DICOM restricts the filenames on DICOM media to 8 characters (some systems wrongly use 8.3, but this does not conform to the standard).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] No information must be extracted from these names (PS3.10 Section 6.2.3.2).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] This is a common source of problems with media created by developers who did not read the specifications carefully.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] This is a historical requirement to maintain compatibility with older existing systems.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] It also mandates the presence of a media directory, the DICOMDIR file, which provides index and summary information for all the DICOM files on the media.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The DICOMDIR information provides substantially greater information about each file than any filename could, so there is less need for meaningful file names.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DICOM files typically have a .dcm file extension if they are not part of a DICOM media (which requires them to be without extension).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The MIME type for DICOM files is defined by RFC 3240 as `application/dicom`.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The Uniform Type Identifier type for DICOM files is `org.nema.dicom`.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] There is also an ongoing media exchange test and "connectathon" process for CD media and network operation that is organized by the IHE organization.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The core application of the DICOM standard is to capture, store and distribute medical images.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] DICOM has reserved the following TCP and UDP port numbers by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA): 104 well-known port for DICOM over Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) or User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The standard recommends but does not require the use of these port numbers.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] According to a paper presented at an international symposium in 2008, the DICOM standard has problems related to data entry.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] "A major disadvantage of the DICOM Standard is the possibility for entering probably too many optional fields.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] This disadvantage is mostly showing in inconsistency of filling all the fields with the data.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Another disadvantage is that the file format admits executable code and may contain malware.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The DICOM standard is used in a wide variety of resources (IHE, HL7 ... a) that are related to images.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] The ISO12052: 2017 and CEN 12052 standards refer to the DICOM standard.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] In December 2023, cybersecurity researcher Sina Yazdanmehr unveiled a critical security issue within the Store service.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] This revelation, presented at Black Hat Briefings, demonstrated the potential for malicious actors to manipulate existing series of medical images.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Yazdanmehr's research highlighted the alarming capability of attackers to destroy a series of images or introduce misleading indicators of illness.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Ensuring the security of patient data within DICOM is critical, as these files often contain sensitive personal health information (PHI).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Security measures for DICOM data include encryption, access control, and auditing mechanisms to prevent unauthorized access, modification, or disclosure of patient information.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Compliance with regulations such as the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) in the United States and the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) in Europe is essential for protecting patient privacy and ensuring the integrity of medical records.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] De-identification of DICOM refers to the process of removing or anonymizing personal health information (PHI) from medical images to protect patient privacy.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] This process is vital for sharing medical data for research, educational purposes, or public health activities while complying with privacy regulations.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Techniques for de-identification involve stripping out or masking identifiable data elements within the DICOM metadata, such as patient names, birth dates, and other unique identifiers.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/dicom] Ensuring thorough de-identification is crucial to balance the benefits of data sharing with the obligation to maintain patient confidentiality.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] In its simplest form, a fluoroscope consists of an X-ray source and a fluorescent screen, between which a patient is placed.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] However, since the 1950s most fluoroscopes have included X-ray image intensifiers and cameras as well, to improve the image's visibility and make it available on a remote display screen.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] For many decades, fluoroscopy tended to produce live pictures that were not recorded, but since the 1960s, as technology improved, recording and playback became the norm.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Fluoroscopy is similar to radiography and X-ray computed tomography (X-ray CT) in that it generates images using X-rays.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] The original difference was that radiography fixed still images on film, whereas fluoroscopy provided live moving pictures that were not stored.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] However, modern radiography, CT, and fluoroscopy now use digital imaging with image analysis software and data storage and retrieval.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Compared to other x-ray imaging modalities, the source projects from below, leading to horizontally mirrored images.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] In keeping with historical displays, the grayscale remains inverted (radiodense objects such as bones are dark whereas traditionally they would be bright).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Although visible light can be **seen** by the naked eye (and thus forms images that people can look at), it does not penetrate most objects (only translucent or transparent ones).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] In contrast, X-rays can penetrate a wider variety of objects (such as the human body), but they are invisible to the naked eye.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] To take advantage of the penetration for image-forming purposes, one must somehow convert the X-rays' intensity variations (which correspond to material contrast and thus image contrast) into a form that is visible.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Classic film-based radiography achieves this by the variable chemical changes that the X-rays induce in the film, and classic fluoroscopy achieves it by fluorescence, in which certain materials convert X-ray energy (or other parts of the spectrum) into visible light.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] This use of fluorescent materials to make a viewing scope is how fluoroscopy got its name.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] As the X-rays pass through the patient, they are attenuated by varying amounts as they pass through or reflect off the different tissues of the body, casting an X-ray shadow of the radiopaque tissues (such as bone tissue) on the fluorescent screen.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Images on the screen are produced as the unattenuated or mildly attenuated X-rays from radiolucent tissues interact with atoms in the screen through the photoelectric effect, giving their energy to the electrons.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] While much of the energy given to the electrons is dissipated as heat, a fraction of it is given off as visible light.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Early radiologists would adapt their eyes to view the dim fluoroscopic images by sitting in darkened rooms, or by wearing red adaptation goggles.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] After the development of X-ray image intensifiers, the images were bright enough to see without goggles under normal ambient light.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Fluoroscopy has become an important tool in medical imaging to render moving pictures during a surgery or any other procedure.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Fluoroscopy is used in various types of surgical procedure, such as orthopaedic surgery and podiatric surgery.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] In both of those, it is used to guide fracture reduction and in use in certain procedures that have extensive hardware.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Specifically, once the fracture is realigned, a surgeon will (with the assistance of their surgical technologist) drill a guide pin into the bone tissue and use fluoroscopy to insure proper angle of the pin - then a cannulated drill bit is inserted over the pin to prepare a ‘hole’ for a bone screw.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] If the surgeon prefers a different angle, they simply reverse the pin and redrill.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Fluoroscopy will be use for each screw placed -which has greatly improved proper fracture heal due to more accurate reduction.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] In urology, fluoroscopy is used in retrograde pyelography and micturating cystourethrography to detect various abnormalities related to the urinary system.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Fluoroscopy is used to confirm needle and guide wire location when placing a nephrostomy.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] It is also increasingly employed during percutaneous nephrolithotomy, where low-dose pulsed fluoroscopy techniques have been shown to significantly reduce radiation exposure for both patients and surgical staff without compromising procedural outcomes.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] In cardiology, fluoroscopy is used for diagnostic angiography, percutaneous coronary interventions, and device implantation (pacemakers, implantable cardioverter-defibrillators, and cardiac resynchronization devices).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Fluoroscopy can be used to examine the digestive system using a substance that is opaque to X-rays (usually barium sulfate or gastrografin), which is introduced into the digestive system either by swallowing or as an enema.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] This is normally as part of a double-contrast technique, using positive and negative contrast.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Barium sulfate coats the walls of the digestive tract (positive contrast), which allows the shape of the digestive tract to be outlined as white or clear on an X-ray.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Air may then be introduced (negative contrast), which looks black on the film.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] The barium meal is an example of a contrast agent swallowed to examine the upper digestive tract.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] While soluble barium compounds are very toxic, the insoluble barium sulfate is nontoxic because its low solubility prevents the body from absorbing it.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Investigations of the gastrointestinal tract include barium enemas, defecating proctograms, barium meals and swallows, and enteroclysis.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Fluoroscopy is also used in airport security scanners to check for hidden weapons or bombs.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] These machines use lower doses of radiation than medical fluoroscopy.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] The reason for higher doses in medical applications is that they are more demanding about tissue contrast, and for the same reason they sometimes require contrast media.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Within months of this discovery, the first crude fluoroscopes were created.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] These experimental fluoroscopes were simply thin cardboard screens that had been coated on the inside with a layer of fluorescent metal salt, attached to a funnel-shaped cardboard eyeshade which excluded room light with a viewing eyepiece which the user held up to his eye.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] The fluoroscopic image obtained in this way was quite faint.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] The placement of the radiologist behind the screen also resulted in significant dosing of the radiologist.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] In the late 1890s, Thomas Edison began investigating materials for ability to fluoresce when X-rayed, and by the turn of the century he had invented a fluoroscope with sufficient image intensity to be commercialized.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Edison had quickly discovered that calcium tungstate screens produced brighter images.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Edison, however, abandoned his research in 1903 because of the health hazards that accompanied the use of these early devices.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Clarence Dally, a glass blower of lab equipment and tubes at Edison's laboratory was repeatedly exposed, developing radiation poisoning, later dying from an aggressive cancer.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Edison himself damaged an eye in testing these early fluoroscopes.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Another factor was that plain films inherently offered recording of the image in a simple and inexpensive way, whereas recording and playback of fluoroscopy remained a more complex and expensive proposition for decades to come (discussed in detail below).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Red adaptation goggles were developed by Wilhelm Trendelenburg in 1916 to address the problem of dark adaptation of the eyes, previously studied by Antoine Beclere.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] The resulting red light from the goggles' filtration correctly sensitized the physician's eyes prior to the procedure, while still allowing him to receive enough light to function normally.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] More trivial uses of the technology emerged in the early 1920s, including a shoe-fitting fluoroscope that was used at shoe stores and department stores.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Concerns regarding the impact of frequent or poorly controlled use were expressed in the late 1940s and 1950s.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Issues raised by doctors and health professionals included the potential for burns to the skin, damage to bone, and abnormal development of the feet.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] These concerns lead to the development of new guidelines, regulations and ultimately the practice's end by the early 1960s.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Shoe salesmen and industry representatives sometimes defended their use, claiming that there was no evidence of harm, and that their use prevented harm to the feet caused by poorly-fitted shoes.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Fluoroscopy was discontinued in shoe-fitting because the radiation exposure risk outweighed the trivial benefit.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Only important applications such as health care, bodily safety, food safety, nondestructive testing, and scientific research meet the risk-benefit threshold for use.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Analog electronics revolutionized fluoroscopy.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] The development of the X-ray image intensifier by Westinghouse in the late 1940s in combination with closed circuit TV cameras of the 1950s allowed for brighter pictures and better radiation protection.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] The red adaptation goggles became obsolete as image intensifiers allowed the light produced by the fluorescent screen to be amplified and made visible in a lighted room.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] The addition of the camera enabled viewing of the image on a monitor, allowing a radiologist to view the images in a separate room away from the risk of radiation exposure.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] The commercialization of video tape recorders beginning in 1956 allowed the TV images to be recorded and played back at will.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Digital electronics were applied to fluoroscopy beginning in the early 1960s, when Frederick G.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] McNulty (1929–2014) at Automation Industries, Inc., then, in El Segundo, California produced on a fluoroscope the world's first image to be digitally generated in real-time, while developing a later commercialized portable apparatus for the onboard nondestructive testing of naval aircraft.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Square wave signals were detected on a fluorescent screen to create the image.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] From the late 1980s onward, digital imaging technology was reintroduced to fluoroscopy after development of improved detector systems.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Modern improvements in screen phosphors, digital image processing, image analysis, and flat panel detectors have allowed for increased image quality while minimizing the radiation dose to the patient.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Modern fluoroscopes use caesium iodide (CsI) screens and produce noise-limited images, ensuring that the minimal radiation dose results while still obtaining images of acceptable quality.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Many names exist in the medical literature for moving pictures taken with X-rays.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] They include **fluoroscopy**, **fluorography**, **cinefluorography**, **photofluorography**, **fluororadiography**, **kymography** (**electrokymography**, **roentgenkymography**), **cineradiography** (**cine**), **videofluorography**, and **videofluoroscopy**.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Today, the word "fluoroscopy" is widely understood to be a hypernym of all the aforementioned terms, which explains why it is the most commonly used and why the others are declining in usage.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] As soon as X-rays (and their application of seeing inside the body) were discovered in the 1890s, both looking and recording were pursued.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] The quest for recorded moving images, though, was a more complex challenge.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] In the 1890s, moving pictures of any kind (whether taken with visible light or with invisible radiation) were emerging technologies.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Because the word "photography" (literally "recording/engraving with light") was long since established as connoting a still-image medium, the word "cinematography" (literally "recording/engraving movement") was coined for the new medium of visible-light moving pictures.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Soon, several new words were coined for achieving moving radiographic pictures.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] This was often done either by filming a simple fluoroscopic screen with a movie camera (variously called fluorography, cinefluorography, photofluorography, or fluororadiography) or by taking serial radiographs rapidly to serve as the frames in a movie (cineradiography).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Either way, the resulting film reel could be displayed by a movie projector.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Thus, electrokymography and roentgenkymography were among the early ways to record images from a simple fluoroscopic screen.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Television also was under early development during these decades (1890s–1920s), but even after commercial TV began widespread adoption after World War II, it remained a live-only medium for a time.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] In the mid-1950s, a commercialized ability to capture the moving pictures of television onto magnetic tape (with a video tape recorder) was developed.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] This soon led to the addition of the "video-" prefix to the words fluorography and fluoroscopy, with the words videofluorography and videofluoroscopy attested since 1960.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] In the 1970s, videotape moved from TV studios and medical imaging into the consumer market with home video via VHS and Betamax, and those formats were also incorporated into medical video equipment.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Thus, over time the cameras and recording media for fluoroscopic imaging have progressed: The original kind of fluoroscopy, and the common kind for its first half-century of existence, simply used none, because for most diagnosis and treatment, they were not essential.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] For those investigations that needed to be transmitted or recorded (such as for training or research), movie cameras using film (such as 16 mm film) were the medium.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] In the 1950s, analog electronic video cameras (at first only producing live output, but later using video tape recorders) appeared.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Since the 1990s, digital video cameras, flat panel detectors, and storage of data to local servers or (more recently) secure cloud servers have been used.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Cineradiography records 30-frame/second fluoroscopic images of internal organs such as the heart taken during injection of contrast dye to better visualize regions of stenosis, or to record motility in the body's gastrointestinal tract.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] The predigital technology is being replaced with digital imaging systems.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Some of these decrease the frame rate, but also decrease the absorbed dose of radiation to the patient.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] As they improve, frame rates will likely increase.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Today, owing to technological convergence, the word "fluoroscopy" is widely understood to be a hypernym of all the earlier names for moving pictures taken with X-rays, both live and recorded.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Also owing to technological convergence, radiography, CT, and fluoroscopy are now all digital imaging modes using X-rays with image-analysis software and easy data storage and retrieval.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Many decades may pass before the earlier hyponyms fall into disuse, not the least because the day when 4D CT displaces all earlier forms of moving X-ray imaging may yet be distant.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] The use of X-rays, a form of ionizing radiation, requires the potential risks from a procedure to be carefully balanced with the benefits of the procedure to the patient.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Because the patient must be exposed to a continuous source of X-rays instead of a momentary pulse, a fluoroscopy procedure generally subjects a patient to a higher absorbed dose of radiation than an ordinary (still) radiograph.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] In the first half of the 20th century, shoe-fitting fluoroscopes were used in shoe stores, but their use was discontinued because it is no longer considered acceptable to use radiation exposure, however small the dose, for nonessential purposes.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Much research has been directed toward reducing radiation exposure, and recent advances in fluoroscopy technology such as digital image processing and flat panel detectors, have resulted in much lower radiation doses than former procedures.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Because fluoroscopy involves the use of X-rays, a form of ionizing radiation, fluoroscopic procedures pose a potential for increasing the patient's risk of radiation-induced cancer.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] In addition to the cancer risk and other stochastic radiation effects, deterministic radiation effects have also been observed ranging from mild erythema, equivalent of a sunburn, to more serious burns.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Radiation doses to the patient depend greatly both on the size of the patient and length of the procedure, with typical skin dose rates quoted as 20–50 mGy/min.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Exposure times vary depending on the procedure being performed, ranging from minutes to hours.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] A study of radiation-induced skin injuries was performed in 1994 by the U.S.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) followed by an advisory to minimize further fluoroscopy-induced injuries.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] The problem of radiation injuries due to fluoroscopy has been further addressed in review articles in 2000 and 2010.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] While deterministic radiation effects are a possibility, radiation burns are not typical in standard fluoroscopic procedures.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Most procedures sufficiently long in duration to produce radiation burns are part of necessary life-saving operations.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] X-ray image intensifiers generally have radiation-reducing systems such as pulsed rather than constant radiation, along with "last image hold", which "freezes" the screen and makes it available for examination without exposing the patient to unnecessary radiation.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Image intensifiers have been introduced that increase the brightness of the screen, so that the patient can be exposed to a lower dose of X-rays.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Whilst this reduces the risk of ionisation occurring, it does not remove it entirely.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] The invention of X-ray image intensifiers in the 1950s allowed the image on the screen to be visible under normal lighting conditions, and provided the option of recording the images with a conventional camera.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Subsequent improvements included the coupling of, at first, video cameras, and later, digital cameras using image sensors such as charge-coupled devices or active pixel sensors to permit recording of moving images and electronic storage of still images.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Modern image intensifiers no longer use a separate fluorescent screen.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Instead, a caesium iodide phosphor is deposited directly on the photocathode of the intensifier tube.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] On a typical general-purpose system, the output image is approximately 105 times brighter than the input image.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] This brightness gain comprises a flux gain (amplification of photon number) and minification gain (concentration of photons from a large input screen onto a small output screen) each of about 100.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] This level of gain is sufficient that quantum noise, due to the limited number of X-ray photons, is a significant factor limiting image quality.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Image intensifiers are available with input diameters up to 45 cm, and a resolution of around two to three line pairs/mm.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] The introduction of flat-panel detectors allows for the replacement of the image intensifier in fluoroscope design.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Flat-panel detectors offer increased sensitivity to X-rays, so have the potential to reduce patient radiation dose.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Temporal resolution is also improved over image intensifiers, reducing motion blurring.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Contrast ratio is also improved over image intensifiers; flat-panel detectors are linear over a very wide latitude, whereas image intensifiers have a maximum contrast ratio of about 35:1.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Spatial resolution is roughly equal, although an image intensifier operating in magnification mode may be slightly better than a flat panel.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Flat-panel detectors are considerably more expensive to purchase and repair than image intensifiers, so their use adoption is primarily in specialties that require high-speed imaging, e.g., vascular imaging and cardiac catheterization.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] A number of substances have been used as radiocontrast agents, including silver, bismuth, caesium, thorium, tin, zirconium, tantalum, tungsten, and lanthanide compounds.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] The use of thoria (thorium dioxide) as an agent was rapidly stopped, as thorium causes liver cancer.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Most modern injected radiographic positive contrast media are iodine-based.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Iodinated contrast comes in two forms - ionic and nonionic compounds.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Nonionic contrast is significantly more expensive than ionic (about three to five times the cost), but nonionic contrast tends to be safer for the patient, causing fewer allergic reactions and uncomfortable side effects such as hot sensations or flushing.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Most imaging centers now use nonionic contrast exclusively, finding that the benefits to patients outweigh the expense.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Negative radiographic contrast agents are air and carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] The latter is easily absorbed by the body and causes less spasm.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] It can also be injected into the blood, where air absolutely cannot due to the risk of an air embolism.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] In addition to spatial blurring factors that plague all X-ray imaging devices, caused by such things as Lubberts effect, K-fluorescence reabsorption, and electron range, fluoroscopic systems also experience temporal blurring due to system latency.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] This temporal blurring has the effect of averaging frames together.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] While this helps reduce noise in images with stationary objects, it creates motion blurring for moving objects.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/fluoroscopy] Temporal blurring also complicates measurements of system performance for fluoroscopic systems.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In a limited comparison, these technologies can be considered forms of medical imaging in another discipline of medical instrumentation.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] As of 2010, 5 billion medical imaging studies had been conducted worldwide.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Radiation exposure from medical imaging in 2006 made up about 50% of total ionizing radiation exposure in the United States.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] As of 2015, annual shipments of medical imaging chips amount to 46 million units and $1.1 billion.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The term "noninvasive" is used to denote a procedure where no instrument is introduced into a patient's body, which is the case for most imaging techniques used.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In 1972, engineer Godfrey Hounsfield from the British company EMI invented the X-ray computed tomography device for head diagnosis, which is commonly referred to as computed tomography (CT).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The CT nucleus method is based on the projecting X-rays through a section of the human head, which are then processed by computer to reconstruct the cross-sectional image, known as image reconstruction.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In 1975, EMI successfully developed a CT device for the entire body, enabling the clear acquisition of tomographic images of various parts of the human body.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] This revolutionary diagnostic technique earned Hounsfield and physicist Allan Cormack the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1979.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Digital image processing technology for medical applications was inducted into the Space Foundation's Space Technology Hall of Fame in 1994.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] By 2010, over 5 billion medical imaging studies had been conducted worldwide.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Radiation exposure from medical imaging in 2006 accounted for about 50% of total ionizing radiation exposure in the United States.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] As of 2015, annual shipments of medical imaging chips reached 46 million units, generating a market value of $1.1 billion.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In the clinical context, "invisible light" medical imaging is generally equated to radiology or "clinical imaging".
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] "Visible light" medical imaging involves digital video or still pictures that can be seen without special equipment.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Dermatology and wound care are two modalities that use visible light imagery.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Interpretation of medical images is generally undertaken by a physician specialising in radiology known as a *radiologist*; however, this may be undertaken by any healthcare professional who is trained and certified in radiological clinical evaluation.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Increasingly interpretation is being undertaken by non-physicians, for example radiographers frequently train in interpretation as part of expanded practice.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Diagnostic radiography designates the technical aspects of medical imaging and in particular the acquisition of medical images.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The radiographer (also known as a radiologic technologist) is usually responsible for acquiring medical images of diagnostic quality; although other professionals may train in this area, notably some radiological interventions performed by radiologists are done so without a radiographer.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Many of the techniques developed for medical imaging also have scientific and industrial applications.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Two forms of radiographic images are in use in medical imaging.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Projection radiography and fluoroscopy, with the latter being useful for catheter guidance.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] These 2D techniques are still in wide use despite the advance of 3D tomography due to the low cost, high resolution, and depending on the application, lower radiation dosages with 2D technique.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] This imaging modality uses a wide beam of X-rays for image acquisition and is the first imaging technique available in modern medicine.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The MRI machine emits a radio frequency (RF) pulse at the resonant frequency of the hydrogen atoms on water molecules.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Radio frequency antennas ("RF coils") send the pulse to the area of the body to be examined.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The RF pulse is absorbed by protons, causing their direction with respect to the primary magnetic field to change.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] When the RF pulse is turned off, the protons "relax" back to alignment with the primary magnet and emit radio waves in the process.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] This radio-frequency emission from the hydrogen atoms on water is what is detected and reconstructed into an image.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The resonant frequency of a spinning magnetic dipole (of which protons are one example) is called the Larmor frequency and is determined by the strength of the main magnetic field and the chemical environment of the nuclei of interest.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Like CT, MRI traditionally creates a two-dimensional image of a thin "slice" of the body and is therefore considered a tomographic imaging technique.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Modern MRI instruments are capable of producing images in the form of 3D blocks, which may be considered a generalization of the single-slice, tomographic concept.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Unlike CT, MRI does not involve the use of ionizing radiation and is therefore not associated with the same health hazards.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] However, there are well-identified health risks associated with tissue heating from exposure to the RF field and the presence of implanted devices in the body, such as pacemakers.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] These risks are strictly controlled as part of the design of the instrument and the scanning protocols used.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Because CT and MRI are sensitive to different tissue properties, the appearances of the images obtained with the two techniques differ markedly.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In CT, X-rays must be blocked by some form of dense tissue to create an image, so the image quality when looking at soft tissues will be poor.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In MRI, while any nucleus with a net nuclear spin can be used, the proton of the hydrogen atom remains the most widely used, especially in the clinical setting, because it is so ubiquitous and returns a large signal.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] This nucleus, present in water molecules, allows the excellent soft-tissue contrast achievable with MRI.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] A number of different pulse sequences can be used for specific MRI diagnostic imaging (multiparametric MRI or mpMRI).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] For example, imaging of prostate tumors is better accomplished using T2-MRI and DWI-MRI than T2-weighted imaging alone.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The number of applications of mpMRI for detecting disease in various organs continues to expand, including liver studies, breast tumors, pancreatic tumors, and assessing the effects of vascular disruption agents on cancer tumors.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Nuclear medicine encompasses both diagnostic imaging and treatment of disease, and may also be referred to as molecular medicine or molecular imaging and therapeutics.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Nuclear medicine uses certain properties of isotopes and the energetic particles emitted from radioactive material to diagnose or treat various pathology.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Different from the typical concept of anatomic radiology, nuclear medicine enables assessment of physiology.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] This function-based approach to medical evaluation has useful applications in most subspecialties, notably oncology, neurology, and cardiology.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] *Gamma cameras* and *PET scanners* are used in e.g. scintigraphy, SPECT and PET to detect regions of biologic activity that may be associated with a disease.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Relatively short-lived isotope, such as 99mTc is administered to the patient.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Isotopes are often preferentially absorbed by biologically active tissue in the body, and can be used to identify tumors or fracture points in bone.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Images are acquired after collimated photons are detected by a crystal that gives off a light signal, which is in turn amplified and converted into count data.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Fiduciary markers are used in a wide range of medical imaging applications.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Images of the same subject produced with two different imaging systems may be correlated (called image registration) by placing a fiduciary marker in the area imaged by both systems.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In this case, a marker which is visible in the images produced by both imaging modalities must be used.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] By this method, functional information from SPECT or positron emission tomography can be related to anatomical information provided by magnetic resonance imaging (MRI).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Similarly, fiducial points established during MRI can be correlated with brain images generated by magnetoencephalography to localize the source of brain activity.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Medical ultrasound uses high frequency broadband sound waves in the megahertz range that are reflected by tissue to varying degrees to produce (up to 3D) images.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] This is commonly associated with imaging the fetus in pregnant women.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Uses of ultrasound are much broader, however.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Other important uses include imaging the abdominal organs, heart, breast, muscles, tendons, arteries and veins.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Ultrasound is also used as a popular research tool for capturing raw data, that can be made available through an ultrasound research interface, for the purpose of tissue characterization and implementation of new image processing techniques.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The concepts of ultrasound differ from other medical imaging modalities in the fact that it is operated by the transmission and receipt of sound waves.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The high frequency sound waves are sent into the tissue and depending on the composition of the different tissues; the signal will be attenuated and returned at separate intervals.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] A path of reflected sound waves in a multilayered structure can be defined by an input acoustic impedance (ultrasound sound wave) and the Reflection and transmission coefficients of the relative structures.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] It is very safe to use and does not appear to cause any adverse effects.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] It is also relatively inexpensive and quick to perform.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Ultrasound scanners can be taken to critically ill patients in intensive care units, avoiding the danger caused while moving the patient to the radiology department.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The real-time moving image obtained can be used to guide drainage and biopsy procedures.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Doppler capabilities on modern scanners allow the blood flow in arteries and veins to be assessed.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Elastography is a relatively new imaging modality that maps the elastic properties of soft tissue.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] This modality emerged in the last two decades.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Elastography is useful in medical diagnoses, as elasticity can discern healthy from unhealthy tissue for specific organs/growths.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] For example, cancerous tumours will often be harder than the surrounding tissue, and diseased livers are stiffer than healthy ones.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] There are several elastographic techniques based on the use of ultrasound, magnetic resonance imaging and tactile imaging.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The wide clinical use of ultrasound elastography is a result of the implementation of technology in clinical ultrasound machines.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Main branches of ultrasound elastography include Quasistatic Elastography/Strain Imaging, Shear Wave Elasticity Imaging (SWEI), Acoustic Radiation Force Impulse imaging (ARFI), Supersonic Shear Imaging (SSI), and Transient Elastography.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In the last decade, a steady increase of activities in the field of elastography is observed demonstrating successful application of the technology in various areas of medical diagnostics and treatment monitoring.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Photoacoustic imaging is a recently developed hybrid biomedical imaging modality based on the photoacoustic effect.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] It combines the advantages of optical absorption contrast with an ultrasonic spatial resolution for deep imaging in (optical) diffusive or quasi-diffusive regime.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Recent studies have shown that photoacoustic imaging can be used in vivo for tumor angiogenesis monitoring, blood oxygenation mapping, functional brain imaging, and skin melanoma detection, etc.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Tomography is the imaging by sections or sectioning.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] When ultrasound is used to image the heart it is referred to as an echocardiogram.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Echocardiography allows detailed structures of the heart, including chamber size, heart function, the valves of the heart, as well as the pericardium (the sac around the heart) to be seen.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Echocardiography uses 2D, 3D, and Doppler imaging to create pictures of the heart and visualize the blood flowing through each of the four heart valves.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Echocardiography is widely used in an array of patients ranging from those experiencing symptoms, such as shortness of breath or chest pain, to those undergoing cancer treatments.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Transthoracic ultrasound has been proven to be safe for patients of all ages, from infants to the elderly, without risk of harmful side effects or radiation, differentiating it from other imaging modalities.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Echocardiography is one of the most commonly used imaging modalities in the world due to its portability and use in a variety of applications.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In emergency situations, echocardiography is quick, easily accessible, and able to be performed at the bedside, making it the modality of choice for many physicians.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] FNIR Is a relatively new non-invasive imaging technique.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] NIRS (near infrared spectroscopy) is used for the purpose of functional neuroimaging and has been widely accepted as a brain imaging technique.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Using superparamagnetic iron oxide nanoparticles, magnetic particle imaging (MPI) is a developing diagnostic imaging technique used for tracking superparamagnetic iron oxide nanoparticles.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The primary advantage is the high sensitivity and specificity, along with the lack of signal decrease with tissue depth.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] MPI has been used in medical research to image cardiovascular performance, neuroperfusion, and cell tracking.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Organizations in the medical imaging industry include manufacturers of imaging equipment, freestanding radiology facilities, and hospitals.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The global market for manufactured devices was estimated at $5 billion in 2018.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Notable manufacturers included Fujifilm, GE HealthCare, Siemens Healthineers, Philips, Shimadzu, Canon, Carestream Health, Hologic, United Imaging, and Esaote.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In 2016, the manufacturing industry was characterized as oligopolistic and mature; new entrants included in Samsung and Neusoft Medical.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In 2024, Fischer MVL in India began manufacturing MRI machines.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Other companies in India include Allengers, Skanray, and BPL Medical Technologies.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In 2016, Toshiba exited the industry by selling its medical imaging division to Canon, which was ultimately renamed to Canon.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In 2019, Hitachi exited the industry by selling its business to Fujifilm for about $1.6 billion.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The simpler x-ray machines were being commoditized by 1998, when Kodak had about 30% market share globally; Kodak later sold its medical imaging business in 2007 and the business was ultimately renamed to Carestream Health.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In the 1970s, CT scanners were introduced, followed by MRI machines in the 1980s, with GE leading in both.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Digital radiography has replaced older computed radiography over time, which reduces radiation doses.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In the United States, as estimate as of 2015 places the US market for imaging scans at about $100b, with 60% occurring in hospitals and 40% occurring in freestanding clinics, such as the RadNet chain.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Medical imaging may be indicated in pregnancy because of pregnancy complications, a pre-existing disease or an acquired disease in pregnancy, or routine prenatal care.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) without MRI contrast agents as well as obstetric ultrasonography are not associated with any risk for the mother or the fetus, and are the imaging techniques of choice for pregnant women.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Projectional radiography, CT scan and nuclear medicine imaging result some degree of ionizing radiation exposure, but have with a few exceptions much lower absorbed doses than what are associated with fetal harm.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] At higher dosages, effects can include miscarriage, birth defects and intellectual disability.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The amount of data obtained in a single MR or CT scan is very extensive.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Some of the data that radiologists discard could save patients time and money, while reducing their exposure to radiation and risk of complications from invasive procedures.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Another approach for making the procedures more efficient is based on utilizing additional constraints, e.g., in some medical imaging modalities one can improve the efficiency of the data acquisition by taking into account the fact the reconstructed density is positive.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Volume rendering techniques have been developed to enable CT, MRI and ultrasound scanning software to produce 3D images for the physician.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Traditionally CT and MRI scans produced 2D static output on film.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] To produce 3D images, many scans are made and then combined by computers to produce a 3D model, which can then be manipulated by the physician.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] 3D ultrasounds are produced using a somewhat similar technique.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In diagnosing disease of the viscera of the abdomen, ultrasound is particularly sensitive on imaging of biliary tract, urinary tract and female reproductive organs (ovary, fallopian tubes).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] As for example, diagnosis of gallstone by dilatation of common bile duct and stone in the common bile duct.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] With the ability to visualize important structures in great detail, 3D visualization methods are a valuable resource for the diagnosis and surgical treatment of many pathologies.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] It was a key resource for the famous, but ultimately unsuccessful attempt by Singaporean surgeons to separate Iranian twins Ladan and Laleh Bijani in 2003.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The 3D equipment was used previously for similar operations with great success.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Some of these techniques are still at a research stage and not yet used in clinical routines.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Neuroimaging has also been used in experimental circumstances to allow people (especially disabled persons) to control outside devices, acting as a brain computer interface.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Many medical imaging software applications are used for non-diagnostic imaging, specifically because they do not have an FDA approval and not allowed to use in clinical research for patient diagnosis.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Note that many clinical research studies are not designed for patient diagnosis anyway.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Used primarily in ultrasound imaging, capturing the image produced by a medical imaging device is required for archiving and telemedicine applications.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In most scenarios, a frame grabber is used in order to capture the video signal from the medical device and relay it to a computer for further processing and operations.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The Digital Imaging and Communication in Medicine (DICOM) Standard is used globally to store, exchange, and transmit medical images.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The DICOM Standard incorporates protocols for imaging techniques such as radiography, computed tomography (CT), magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), ultrasound, and radiation therapy.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Medical imaging techniques produce very large amounts of data, especially from CT, MRI and PET modalities.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] As a result, storage and communications of electronic image data are prohibitive without the use of compression.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] JPEG 2000 image compression is used by the DICOM standard for storage and transmission of medical images.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The cost and feasibility of accessing large image data sets over low or various bandwidths are further addressed by use of another DICOM standard, called JPIP, to enable efficient streaming of the JPEG 2000 compressed image data.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] There has been growing trend to migrate from on-premise PACS to a cloud-based PACS, which can provide generative AI and other tools to improve diagnostic accuracy with greater fidelity and analysis, yet unresolved issues of bias and interpretation remain, as of 2025.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Medical imaging has become a major tool in clinical trials since it enables rapid diagnosis with visualization and quantitative assessment.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] A typical clinical trial goes through multiple phases and can take up to eight years.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Clinical endpoints or outcomes are used to determine whether the therapy is safe and effective.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Once a patient reaches the endpoint, he or she is generally excluded from further experimental interaction.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Trials that rely solely on clinical endpoints are very costly as they have long durations and tend to need large numbers of patients.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In contrast to clinical endpoints, surrogate endpoints have been shown to cut down the time required to confirm whether a drug has clinical benefits.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Imaging biomarkers (a characteristic that is objectively measured by an imaging technique, which is used as an indicator of pharmacological response to a therapy) and surrogate endpoints have shown to facilitate the use of small group sizes, obtaining quick results with good statistical power.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Imaging is able to reveal subtle change that is indicative of the progression of therapy that may be missed out by more subjective, traditional approaches.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Statistical bias is reduced as the findings are evaluated without any direct patient contact.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Imaging techniques such as positron emission tomography (PET) and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) are routinely used in oncology and neuroscience areas.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] For example, measurement of tumour shrinkage is a commonly used surrogate endpoint in solid tumour response evaluation.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] This allows for faster and more objective assessment of the effects of anticancer drugs.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In Alzheimer's disease, MRI scans of the entire brain can accurately assess the rate of hippocampal atrophy, while PET scans can measure the brain's metabolic activity by measuring regional glucose metabolism, and beta-amyloid plaques using tracers such as Pittsburgh compound B (PiB).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Historically less use has been made of quantitative medical imaging in other areas of drug development although interest is growing.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] An imaging centre that is responsible for collecting the images, perform quality control and provide tools for data storage, distribution and analysis.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] It is important for images acquired at different time points are displayed in a standardised format to maintain the reliability of the evaluation.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Certain specialised imaging contract research organizations provide end to end medical imaging services, from protocol design and site management through to data quality assurance and image analysis.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Clinical sites that recruit patients to generate the images to send back to the imaging centre.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Medical imaging can lead to patient and healthcare provider harm through exposure to ionizing radiation, iodinated contrast, magnetic fields, and other hazards.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Lead is the main material used for radiographic shielding against scattered X-rays.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In magnetic resonance imaging, there is MRI RF shielding as well as magnetic shielding to prevent external disturbance of image quality.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Medical imaging are generally covered by laws of medical privacy.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] While there has not been any definitive legal decision in the matter, many studies have indicated that medical imaging contain biometric information that can uniquely identify a person, and as such qualify as PHI and/or special categories of personal data.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The UK General Medical Council's ethical guidelines indicate that the Council does not require consent prior to making recordings of X-ray images.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] However, the same guidance indicates that the images and recordings need to be anonimized, and acknowledges that in deciding whether a recording is anonymised, one should bear in mind that apparently insignificant details may still be capable of identifying a patient.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] As such, one should be particularly careful about the anonymity of a recordings of an X-ray image before using or publishing them without consent in journals and other learning materials, whether they are printed or in an electronic format.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] As per chapter 300 of the *Compendium of U.S.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] While the Copyright Compendium is an agency statutory interpretation and not legally binding, courts are likely to give deference to it if they find it reasonable.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Yet, there is no U.S. federal case law directly addressing the issue of the copyrightability of X-ray images.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] In Germany, X-ray images as well as MRI, medical ultrasound, PET and scintigraphy images are protected by (copyright-like) related rights or neighbouring rights.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] This protection does not require creativity (as would be necessary for *regular* copyright protection) and lasts only for 50 years after image creation, if not published within 50 years, or for 50 years after the first legitimate publication.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The letter of the law grants this right to the "Lichtbildner", i.e. the person who created the image.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The literature seems to uniformly consider the medical doctor, dentist or veterinary physician as the rights holder, which may result from the circumstance that in Germany many X-rays are performed in ambulatory settings.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Medical images created in the United Kingdom will normally be protected by copyright due to "the high level of skill, labour and judgement required to produce a good quality X-ray, particularly to show contrast between bones and various soft tissues".
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The Society of Radiographers believe this copyright is owned by employer (unless the radiographer is self-employed—though even then their contract might require them to transfer ownership to the hospital).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] This copyright owner can grant certain permissions to whoever they wish, without giving up their ownership of the copyright.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] So the hospital and its employees will be given permission to use such radiographic images for the various purposes that they require for medical care.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Physicians employed at the hospital will, in their contracts, be given the right to publish patient information in journal papers or books they write (providing they are made anonymous).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] Patients may also be granted permission to "do what they like with" their own images.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The *Cyber Law in Sweden* states: "Pictures can be protected as photographic works or as photographic pictures.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The former requires a higher level of originality; the latter *protects all types of photographs, also the ones taken* by amateurs, or *within medicine* or science.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/medical-imaging] The protection requires some sort of photographic technique being used, which includes digital cameras as well as holograms created by laser technique.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] A **picture archiving and communication system** (**PACS**) is a medical imaging technology which provides economical storage and convenient access to images from multiple modalities (source machine types).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Electronic images and reports are transmitted digitally via PACS; this eliminates the need to manually file, retrieve, or transport film jackets, the folders used to store and protect X-ray film.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The universal format for PACS image storage and transfer is DICOM (Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Non-image data, such as scanned documents, may be incorporated using consumer industry standard formats like PDF (Portable Document Format), once encapsulated in DICOM.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Combined with available and emerging web technology, PACS has the ability to deliver timely and efficient access to images, interpretations, and related data.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] PACS reduces the physical and time barriers associated with traditional film-based image retrieval, distribution, and display.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Additional types of image formats are always being added.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Clinical areas beyond radiology; cardiology, oncology, gastroenterology, and even the laboratory are creating medical images that can be incorporated into PACS.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] PACS is offered by virtually all the major medical imaging equipment manufacturers, medical IT companies and many independent software companies.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Basic PACS software can be found free on the Internet.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The architecture is the physical implementation of required functionality, or what one sees from the outside.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] There are different views, depending on the user.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] A radiologist typically sees a viewing station, a technologist a QA workstation, while a PACS administrator might spend most of their time in the climate-controlled computer room.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The composite view is rather different for the various vendors.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Typically a PACS consists of a multitude of devices.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The first step in typical PACS systems is the modality.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Modalities are typically computed tomography (CT), ultrasound, nuclear medicine, positron emission tomography (PET), and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Depending on the facility's workflow most modalities send to a quality assurance (QA) workstation, sometimes called a PACS gateway.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The QA workstation is a checkpoint to make sure patient demographics are correct as well as other important attributes of a study.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] If the study information is correct the images are passed to the archive for storage.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The central storage device (archive) stores images and in some cases reports, measurements and other information that resides with the images.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The next step in the PACS workflow is the reading workstations.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The reading workstation is where the radiologist reviews the patient's study and formulates their diagnosis.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Normally tied to the reading workstation is a reporting package that assists the radiologist with dictating the final report.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Reporting software is optional and there are various ways in which doctors prefer to dictate their report.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Ancillary to the workflow mentioned, there is normally CD/DVD authoring software used to burn patient studies for distribution to patients or referring physicians.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The diagram above shows a typical workflow in most imaging centers and hospitals.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Note that this section does not cover integration to a Radiology Information System, Hospital Information System and other such front-end system that relates to the PACS workflow.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] More and more PACS include web-based interfaces to utilize the internet or a wide area network (WAN) as their means of communication, usually via VPN (Virtual Private Network) or SSL (Secure Sockets Layer).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The clients side software may use ActiveX, JavaScript and/or a Java Applet.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] More robust PACS clients are full applications which can utilize the full resources of the computer they are executing on and are unaffected by the frequent unattended Web Browser and Java updates.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] As the need for distribution of images and reports becomes more widespread there is a push for PACS systems to support DICOM part 18 of the DICOM standard.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Web Access to DICOM Objects (WADO) creates the necessary standard to expose images and reports over the web through truly portable medium.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Without stepping outside the focus of the PACS architecture, WADO becomes the solution to cross platform capability and can increase the distribution of images and reports to referring physicians and patients.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] PACS image backup is a critical, but sometimes overlooked, part of the PACS Architecture (see below).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Within the United States, HIPAA requires that backup copies of patient images be made in case of image loss from the PACS.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] There are several methods of backing up the images, but they typically involve automatically sending copies of the images to a separate computer for storage, preferably off-site.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The communication with the PACS server is done through DICOM messages that are similar to DICOM image "headers", but with different attributes.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Images (and other composite instances like Presentation States and Structured Reports) are then retrieved from a PACS server through either a C-MOVE or C-GET request, using the DICOM network protocol.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Retrieval can be performed at the Study, Series or Image (instance) level.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The C-MOVE request specifies where the retrieved instances should be sent (using separate C-STORE messages on one or more separate connections) with an identifier known as the destination Application Entity Title (AE Title).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] For a C-MOVE to work, the server must be configured with mapping of the AE Title to a TCP/IP address and port, and as a consequence the server must know in advance all the AE Titles that it will ever be requested to send images to.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] A C-GET, on the other hand, performs the C-STORE operations on the same connection as the request, and hence does not require that the "server" know the "client" TCP/IP address and port.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] This allows C-GET to work more easily through firewalls and with network address translation, environments in which the incoming TCP C-STORE connections required for C-MOVE may not get through.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The difference between C-MOVE and C-GET is somewhat analogous to the difference between active and passive FTP.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] C-MOVE is most commonly used within enterprises and facilities, whereas C-GET is more practical between enterprises.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] In addition to the traditional DICOM network services, particularly for cross-enterprise use, DICOM (and IHE) define other retrieval mechanisms, including WADO, WADO-WS and most recently WADO-RS.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Digital medical images are typically stored locally on a PACS for retrieval.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] It is important (and required in the United States by the Security Rule's Administrative Safeguards section of HIPAA) that facilities have a means of recovering images in the event of an error or disaster.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] While each facility is different, the goal in image back-up is to make it automatic and as easy to administer as possible.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The hope is that the copies won't be needed; however, disaster recovery and business continuity planning dictates that plans should include maintaining copies of data even when an entire site is temporarily or permanently lost.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Ideally, copies of images should be maintained in several locations, including off-site to provide disaster recovery capabilities.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] In general, PACS data are no different than other business critical data and should be protected with multiple copies at multiple locations.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] As PACS data can be considered protected health information (PHI), regulations may apply, most notably HIPAA and HIPAA Hi-Tech requirements.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Images may be stored both locally and remotely on off-line media such as disk, tape or optical media.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The use of storage systems, using modern data protection technologies has become increasingly common, particularly for larger organizations with greater capacity and performance requirements.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Storage systems may be configured and attached to the PACS server in various ways, either as Direct-Attached Storage (DAS), Network-attached storage (NAS), or via a Storage Area Network (SAN).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] However the storage is attached, enterprise storage systems commonly utilize RAID and other technologies to provide high availability and fault tolerance to protect against failures.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] In the event that it is necessary to reconstruct a PACS partially or completely, some means of rapidly transferring data back to the PACS is required, preferably while the PACS continues to operate.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Modern data storage replication technologies may be applied to PACS information, including the creation of local copies via point-in-time copy for locally protected copies, along with complete copies of data on separate repositories including disk and tape based systems.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Remote copies of data should be created, either by physically moving tapes off-site, or copying data to remote storage systems.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Whenever HIPAA protected data are moved, it should be encrypted, which includes sending via physical tape or replication technologies over WAN to a secondary location.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Other options for creating copies of PACS data include removable media (hard drives, DVDs or other media that can hold many patients' images) that is physically transferred off-site.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] HIPAA HITECH mandates encryption of stored data in many instances or other security mechanisms to avoid penalties for failure to comply.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The back-up infrastructure may also be capable of supporting the migration of images to a new PACS.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Due to the high volume of images that need to be archived many rad centers are migrating their systems to a Cloud-based PACS.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] A full PACS should provide a single point of access for images and their associated data.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] That is, it should support all digital modalities, in all departments, throughout the organisation.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] However, until PACS penetration is complete, individual islands of digital imaging not yet connected to a central PACS may exist.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] These may take the form of a localized, modality-specific network of modalities, workstations and storage (a so-called "mini-PACS"), or may consist of a small cluster of modalities directly connected to reading workstations without long-term storage or management.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Such systems are also often not connected to the departmental information system.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Historically, Ultrasound, Nuclear Medicine and Cardiology Cath Labs are often departments that adopt such an approach.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] More recently, Full Field digital mammography (FFDM) has taken a similar approach, largely because of the large image size, highly specialized reading workflow and display requirements, and intervention by regulators.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The rapid deployment of FFDM in the US following the DMIST study has led to the integration of Digital Mammography and PACS becoming more commonplace.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] All PACS, whether they span the entire enterprise or are localized within a department, should also interface with existing hospital information systems: Hospital information system (HIS) and Radiology Information System (RIS).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Recognition of the importance of integration has led a number of suppliers to develop fully integrated RIS/PACS.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The PACS installation process is complicated requiring time, resources, planning, and testing.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Installation is not complete until the acceptance test is passed.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Acceptance testing of a new installation is a vital step to assure user compliance, functionality, and especially clinical safety.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Take for example the Therac-25, a radiation medical device involved in accidents in which patients were given massive overdoses of radiation, due to unverified software control.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The acceptance test determines whether the PACS is ready for clinical use and marks the warranty timeline while serving as a payment milestone.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The test process varies in time requirements depending on facility size but contract condition of 30-day time limit is not unusual.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] It requires detailed planning and development of testing criteria prior to writing the contract.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] It is a joint process requiring defined test protocols and benchmarks.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] A study determined that the most frequently cited deficiencies were the most costly components.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Failures ranked from most-to-least common are: Workstation; HIS/RIS/ACS broker interfaces; RIS; Computer Monitors; Web-based image distribution system; Modality interfaces; Archive devices; Maintenance; Training; Network; DICOM; Teleradiology; Security; Film digitizer.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] One of the first basic PACS was created in 1972 by Dr Richard J.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The principles of PACS were first discussed at meetings of radiologists in 1982.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Various people are credited with the coinage of the term *PACS*.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Cardiovascular radiologist Dr Andre Duerinckx reported in 1983 that he had first used the term in 1981.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Dr Samuel Dwyer, though, credits Dr Judith M.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Dr Harold Glass, a medical physicist working in London in the early 1990s secured UK Government funding and managed the project over many years which transformed Hammersmith Hospital in London as the first filmless hospital in the United Kingdom.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Dr Glass died a few months after the project came live but is credited with being one of the pioneers of PACS.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The first large-scale PACS installation was in 1982 at the University of Kansas, Kansas City.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] In the US PACS are classified as Medical Devices, and hence if for sale are regulated by the USFDA.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] In general they are subject to Class 2 controls and hence require a 510(k), though individual PACS components may be subject to less stringent general controls.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] Some specific applications, such as the use for primary mammography interpretation, are additionally regulated within the scope of the Mammography Quality Standards Act.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/picture-archiving-and-communication-system] The Society for Imaging Informatics in Medicine (SIIM) is the worldwide professional and trade organization that provides an annual meeting and a peer-reviewed journal to promote research and education about PACS and related digital topics.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] To create an image in conventional radiography, a beam of X-rays is produced by an X-ray generator and it is projected towards the object.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] A certain amount of the X-rays or other radiation are absorbed by the object, dependent on the object's density and structural composition.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The X-rays that pass through the object are captured behind the object by a detector (either photographic film or a digital detector).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The generation of flat two-dimensional images by this technique is called projectional radiography.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] In computed tomography (CT scanning), an X-ray source and its associated detectors rotate around the subject, which itself moves through the conical X-ray beam produced.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Any given point within the subject is crossed from many directions by many different beams at different times.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Information regarding the attenuation of these beams is collated and subjected to computation to generate two-dimensional images on three planes (axial, coronal, and sagittal) which can be further processed to produce a three-dimensional image.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Radiography's origins and fluoroscopy's origins can both be traced to 8 November 1895, when German physics professor Wilhelm Conrad Röntgen discovered the X-ray and noted that, while it could pass through human tissue, it could not pass through bone or metal.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Röntgen referred to the radiation as "X", to indicate that it was an unknown type of radiation.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] He received the first Nobel Prize in Physics for his discovery.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] He noticed a faint green glow from the screen, about 1 metre away.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Röntgen realized some invisible rays coming from the tube were passing through the cardboard to make the screen glow: they were passing through an opaque object to affect the film behind it.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Röntgen discovered X-rays' medical use when he made a picture of his wife's hand on a photographic plate formed due to X-rays.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The photograph of his wife's hand was the first ever photograph of a human body part using X-rays.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The first use of X-rays under clinical conditions was by John Hall-Edwards in Birmingham, England, on 11 January 1896, when he radiographed a needle stuck in the hand of an associate.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] On 14 February 1896, Hall-Edwards also became the first to use X-rays in a surgical operation.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The United States saw its first medical X-ray obtained using a discharge tube of Ivan Pulyui's design.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] In January 1896, on reading of Röntgen's discovery, Frank Austin of Dartmouth College tested all of the discharge tubes in the physics laboratory and found that only the Pulyui tube produced X-rays.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] This was a result of Pulyui's inclusion of an oblique "target" of mica, used for holding samples of fluorescent material, within the tube.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] X-rays were put to diagnostic use very early; for example, Alan Archibald Campbell-Swinton opened a radiographic laboratory in the United Kingdom in 1896, before the dangers of ionizing radiation were discovered.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Indeed, Marie Curie pushed for radiography to be used to treat wounded soldiers in World War I.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Initially, many kinds of staff conducted radiography in hospitals, including physicists, photographers, physicians, nurses, and engineers.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The medical speciality of radiology grew up over many years around the new technology.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] When new diagnostic tests were developed, it was natural for the radiographers to be trained in and to adopt this new technology.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Radiographers now perform fluoroscopy, computed tomography, mammography, ultrasound, nuclear medicine and magnetic resonance imaging as well.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Although a nonspecialist dictionary might define radiography quite narrowly as "taking X-ray images", this has long been only part of the work of "X-ray departments", radiographers, and radiologists.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Initially, radiographs were known as roentgenograms, while *skiagrapher* (from the Ancient Greek words for "shadow" and "writer") was used until about 1918 to mean *radiographer*.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The Japanese term for the radiograph, *rentogen* (レントゲン), shares its etymology with the original English term.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The discipline involving the study of anatomy through the use of radiographic images is known as radiographic anatomy.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Medical radiography acquisition is generally carried out by radiographers, while image analysis is generally done by radiologists.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Some radiographers also specialise in image interpretation.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Medical radiography includes a range of modalities producing many different types of image, each of which has a different clinical application.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The creation of images by exposing an object to X-rays or other high-energy forms of electromagnetic radiation and capturing the resulting remnant beam (or "shadow") as a latent image is known as "projection radiography".
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Bone and some organs (such as lungs) especially lend themselves to projection radiography.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] It is a relatively low-cost investigation with a high diagnostic yield.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The difference between *soft* and *hard* body parts stems mostly from the fact that carbon has a very low X-ray cross section compared to calcium.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Computed tomography or CT scan (previously known as CAT scan, the "A" standing for "axial") uses ionizing radiation (x-ray radiation) in conjunction with a computer to create images of both soft and hard tissues.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] These images look as though the patient was sliced like bread (thus, "tomography" – "tomo" means "slice").
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Though CT uses a higher amount of ionizing x-radiation than diagnostic x-rays (both utilising X-ray radiation), with advances in technology, levels of CT radiation dose and scan times have reduced.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] CT exams are generally short, most lasting only as long as a breath-hold, Contrast agents are also often used, depending on the tissues needing to be seen.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Radiographers perform these examinations, sometimes in conjunction with a radiologist (for instance, when a radiologist performs a CT-guided biopsy).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] DEXA, or bone densitometry, is used primarily for osteoporosis tests.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] It is not projection radiography, as the X-rays are emitted in two narrow beams that are scanned across the patient, 90 degrees from each other.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Usually the hip (head of the femur), lower back (lumbar spine), or heel (calcaneum) are imaged, and the bone density (amount of calcium) is determined and given a number (a T-score).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] It is not used for bone imaging, as the image quality is not good enough to make an accurate diagnostic image for fractures, inflammation, etc.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] It can also be used to measure total body fat, though this is not common.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The radiation dose received from DEXA scans is very low, much lower than projection radiography examinations.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Fluoroscopy is a term invented by Thomas Edison during his early X-ray studies.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The name refers to the fluorescence he saw while looking at a glowing plate bombarded with X-rays.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The technique provides moving projection radiographs.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Fluoroscopy is mainly performed to view movement (of tissue or a contrast agent), or to guide a medical intervention, such as angioplasty, pacemaker insertion, or joint repair/replacement.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The last can often be carried out in the operating theatre, using a portable fluoroscopy machine called a C-arm.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] It can move around the surgery table and make digital images for the surgeon.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Biplanar Fluoroscopy works the same as single plane fluoroscopy except displaying two planes at the same time.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The ability to work in two planes is important for orthopedic and spinal surgery and can reduce operating times by eliminating re-positioning.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Angiography is the use of fluoroscopy to view the cardiovascular system.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] An iodine-based contrast is injected into the bloodstream and watched as it travels around.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Since liquid blood and the vessels are not very dense, a contrast with high density (like the large iodine atoms) is used to view the vessels under X-ray.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Angiography is used to find aneurysms, leaks, blockages (thromboses), new vessel growth, and placement of catheters and stents.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Balloon angioplasty is often done with angiography.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Contrast radiography uses a radiocontrast agent, a type of contrast medium, to make the structures of interest stand out visually from their background.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Contrast agents are required in conventional angiography, and can be used in both projectional radiography and computed tomography (called *contrast CT*).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Although not technically radiographic techniques due to not using X-rays, imaging modalities such as PET and MRI are sometimes grouped in radiography because the radiology department of hospitals handle all forms of imaging.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Treatment using radiation is known as radiotherapy.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Industrial radiography is a method of non-destructive testing where many types of manufactured components can be examined to verify the internal structure and integrity of the specimen.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Industrial Radiography can be performed utilizing either X-rays or gamma rays.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Both are forms of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The difference between various forms of electromagnetic energy is related to the wavelength.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] X and gamma rays have the shortest wavelength and this property leads to the ability to penetrate, travel through, and exit various materials such as carbon steel and other metals.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Specific methods include industrial computed tomography.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Image quality will depend on resolution and density.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Resolution is the ability of an image to show closely spaced structure in the object as separate entities in the image while density is the blackening power of the image.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Sharpness of a radiographic image is strongly determined by the size of the X-ray source.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] This is determined by the area of the electron beam hitting the anode.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] A large photon source results in more blurring in the final image and is worsened by an increase in image formation distance.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] This blurring can be measured as a contribution to the modulation transfer function of the imaging system.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The dosage of radiation applied in radiography varies by procedure.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] For example, the effective dosage of a chest x-ray is 0.1 mSv, while an abdominal CT is 10 mSv.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Nonetheless, radiological organizations, including the Radiological Society of North America (RSNA) and the American College of Radiology (ACR), as well as multiple government agencies, indicate safety standards to ensure that radiation dosage is as low as possible.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Lead is the most common shield against X-rays because of its high density (11,340 kg/m3), stopping power, ease of installation and low cost.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The maximum range of a high-energy photon such as an X-ray in matter is infinite; at every point in the matter traversed by the photon, there is a probability of interaction.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Thus there is a very small probability of no interaction over very large distances.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The shielding of photon beam is therefore exponential (with an attenuation length being close to the radiation length of the material); doubling the thickness of shielding will square the shielding effect.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Starting in the 1950s, personal lead shielding began to be used on directly on patients during all X-rays over the abdomen to intending to protect the gonads (reproductive organs) or a fetus if the patient was pregnant.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Dental X-rays would also typically additionally use lead shielding to protect the thyroid.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] However, a consensus was reached between 2019 and 2021 that lead shielding for routine diagnostic X-rays is not necessary and may in some cases be harmful.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Personal shielding for medical professionals and other people in the room is still recommended.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Rooms where X-rays are performed are lined with lead.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The table in this section shows the recommended thickness of lead shielding for a room where X-rays are performed as function of X-ray energy, from the Recommendations by the Second International Congress of Radiology.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] In response to increased concern by the public over radiation doses and the ongoing progress of best practices, The Alliance for Radiation Safety in Pediatric Imaging was formed within the Society for Pediatric Radiology.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] This initiative has been endorsed and applied by a growing list of various professional medical organizations around the world and has received support and assistance from companies that manufacture equipment used in radiology.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] The World Health Organization and International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) of the United Nations have also been working in this area and have ongoing projects designed to broaden best practices and lower patient radiation dose.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/radiography] Contrary to advice that emphasises only conducting radiographs when in the patient's interest, recent evidence suggests that they are used more frequently when dentists are paid under fee-for-service.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] This article applies in general to reconstruction methods for all kinds of tomography, but some of the terms and physical descriptions refer directly to the reconstruction of X-ray computed tomography.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] The projection of an object, resulting from the tomographic measurement process at a given angle $\theta$ , is made up of a set of line integrals (see Fig.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] A set of many such projections under different angles organized in 2D is called a sinogram (see Fig.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] In X-ray CT, the line integral represents the total attenuation of the beam of X-rays as it travels in a straight line through the object.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] As mentioned above, the resulting image is a 2D (or 3D) model of the attenuation coefficient.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] That is, we wish to find the image $\mu (x,y)$ .
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] The simplest and easiest way to visualise the method of scanning is the system of parallel projection, as used in the first scanners.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] For this discussion we consider the data to be collected as a series of parallel rays, at position r , across a projection at angle $\theta$ .
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] where $\mu (x,y)$ is the attenuation coefficient as a function of position.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] where $f(x,y)$ represents $\mu (x,y)$ and $\delta ()$ is the Dirac delta function.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] This function is known as the Radon transform (or *sinogram*) of the 2D object.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] , the inverse Radon transform formula can be easily derived.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] In theory, the inverse Radon transformation would yield the original image.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] The projection-slice theorem tells us that if we had an infinite number of one-dimensional projections of an object taken at an infinite number of angles, we could perfectly reconstruct the original object, $f(x,y)$ .
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] However, there will only be a finite number of projections available in practice.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Practical reconstruction algorithms have been developed to implement the process of reconstruction of a three-dimensional object from its projections.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] These algorithms are designed largely based on the mathematics of the X-ray transform, statistical knowledge of the data acquisition process and geometry of the data imaging system.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Reconstruction can be made using interpolation.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Assume N projections of $f(x,y)$ are generated at equally spaced angles, each sampled at the same rate.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] The discrete Fourier transform (DFT) on each projection yields sampling in the frequency domain.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Combining all the frequency-sampled projections generates a polar raster in the frequency domain.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] The polar raster is sparse, so interpolation is used to fill the unknown DFT points, and reconstruction can be done through the inverse discrete Fourier transform.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Reconstruction performance may improve by designing methods to change the sparsity of the polar raster, facilitating the effectiveness of interpolation.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] where $R_{0}$ is highest frequency to be evaluated.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] The concentric square raster improves computational efficiency by allowing all the interpolation positions to be on rectangular DFT lattice.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Furthermore, it reduces the interpolation error.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Yet, the Fourier-Transform algorithm has a disadvantage of producing inherently noisy output.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] In practice of tomographic image reconstruction, often a stabilized and discretized version of the inverse Radon transform is used, known as the filtered back projection algorithm.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] where $\Delta \theta$ is the angular spacing between the projections and $k(t)$ is a Radon kernel with frequency response $|\omega |$ .
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] The name *back-projection* comes from the fact that a one-dimensional projection needs to be filtered by a one-dimensional Radon kernel (back-projected) in order to obtain a two-dimensional signal.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] The filter used does not contain DC gain, so adding DC bias may be desirable.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Reconstruction using back-projection allows better resolution than interpolation method described above.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] However, it induces greater noise because the filter is prone to amplify high-frequency content.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] The iterative algorithm is computationally intensive but it allows the inclusion of *a priori* information about the system $f(x,y)$ .
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Let N be the number of projections and $D_{i}$ be the distortion operator for the i th projection taken at an angle $\theta _{i}$ . $\{\lambda _{i}\}$ are a set of parameters to optimize the conversion of iterations.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] An alternative family of recursive tomographic reconstruction algorithms are the algebraic reconstruction techniques and iterative sparse asymptotic minimum variance.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Use of a noncollimated fan beam is common since a collimated beam of radiation is difficult to obtain.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Fan beams will generate series of line integrals, not parallel to each other, as projections.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] The fan-beam system requires a 360-degree range of angles, which imposes mechanical constraints, but it allows faster signal acquisition time, which may be advantageous in certain settings such as in the field of medicine.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Back projection follows a similar two-step procedure that yields reconstruction by computing weighted sum back-projections obtained from filtered projections.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Deep learning methods are widely applied to image reconstruction nowadays and have achieved impressive results in various image reconstruction tasks, including low-dose denoising, sparse-view reconstruction, limited angle tomography and metal artifact reduction.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] An excellent overview can be found in the special issue of IEEE Transaction on Medical Imaging.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] One group of deep learning reconstruction algorithms apply post-processing neural networks to achieve image-to-image reconstruction, where input images are reconstructed by conventional reconstruction methods.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Artifact reduction using the U-Net in limited angle tomography is such an example application.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] However, incorrect structures may occur in an image reconstructed by such a completely data-driven method, as displayed in the figure.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Therefore, integration of known operators into the architecture design of neural networks appears beneficial, as described in the concept of precision learning.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] For example, direct image reconstruction from projection data can be learnt from the framework of filtered back-projection.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Another example is to build neural networks by unrolling iterative reconstruction algorithms.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Except for precision learning, using conventional reconstruction methods with deep learning reconstruction prior is also an alternative approach to improve the image quality of deep learning reconstruction.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Tomographic systems have significant variability in their applications and geometries (locations of sources and detectors).
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] This variability creates the need for very specific, tailored implementations of the processing and reconstruction algorithms.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Thus, most CT manufacturers provide their own custom proprietary software.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] This is done not only to protect intellectual property, but may also be enforced by a government regulatory agency.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Regardless, there are a number of general purpose tomographic reconstruction software packages that have been developed over the last couple decades, both commercial and open-source.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Most of the commercial software packages that are available for purchase focus on processing data for benchtop cone-beam CT systems.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] A few of these software packages include Volume Graphics, InstaRecon, iTomography, Livermore Tomography Tools (LTT), Cone Beam Software Tools (CST), and Bronnikov Algorithms Library.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Some noteworthy examples of open-source reconstruction software include: Reconstruction Toolkit (RTK), CONRAD, TomoPy, the ASTRA toolbox, PYRO-NN, ODL, TIGRE, and LEAP.
[src:medical-imaging-modalities/tomographic-reconstruction] Shown in the gallery is the complete process for a simple object tomography and the following tomographic reconstruction based on ART.
